theorem
Th24: (for S being (SigmaField of X) holds (for N,F being (Function of ( NAT ),S) holds ((( F . ( 0 ) ) = ( N . ( 0 ) ) & (for n being (Element of ( NAT )) holds (( F . ( n + 1 ) ) = ( ( N . ( n + 1 ) ) \ ( N . n ) ) & ( N . n ) c= ( N . ( n + 1 ) )))) implies ( union ( rng F ) ) = ( union ( rng N ) ))))
proof
let S being (SigmaField of X);
let N being (Function of ( NAT ),S),F being (Function of ( NAT ),S);
assume that
A1: ( F . ( 0 ) ) = ( N . ( 0 ) )
and
A2: (for n being (Element of ( NAT )) holds (( F . ( n + 1 ) ) = ( ( N . ( n + 1 ) ) \ ( N . n ) ) & ( N . n ) c= ( N . ( n + 1 ) )));
thus ( union ( rng F ) ) c= ( union ( rng N ) )
proof
let x being set;
assume x in ( union ( rng F ) );
then consider Y being set such that A3: x in Y and A4: Y in ( rng F ) by TARSKI:def 4;
consider n being set such that A5: n in ( dom F ) and A6: Y = ( F . n ) by A4,FUNCT_1:def 3;
reconsider n as (Element of ( NAT )) by A5;
A7: ((ex k being Nat st n = ( k + 1 )) implies (ex Z being set st (x in Z & Z in ( rng N ))))
proof
given k being Nat such that
A8: n = ( k + 1 );

reconsider k as (Element of ( NAT )) by ORDINAL1:def 12;
Y = ( ( N . ( k + 1 ) ) \ ( N . k ) ) by A2,A6,A8;
then x in ( N . ( k + 1 ) ) by A3,XBOOLE_0:def 5;
hence thesis by FUNCT_2:4;
end;
(n = ( 0 ) implies (ex Z being set st (x in Z & Z in ( rng N )))) by A1,A3,A6,FUNCT_2:4;
hence thesis by A7,NAT_1:6,TARSKI:def 4;
